 goals served by comity. No nation is under an unremitting obligation to enforce foreign interests which are fundamentally prejudicial to those of the domestic forum\'94 }{\ltrch\hich\f6\fs20\loch\f6\fs20 at 937 para D.}}}}
}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf2\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s15\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s15\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 What Scalia J does in {\ul\ulc0 Hartford }is to identify that comity seems to be used in two respects. One in relation to the courts, so\'96called \'91judicial comity\'92, that is where judges prefer to not exercise jurisdiction they otherwise have over cases they consider ma
y be more properly adjudicated elsewhere. The second is what is sometimes described in the United States cases as \'91prescriptive comity\'92. This is the respect that legislatures afford each other by limiting the reach of their laws. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s15\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s15\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 Thus when a court is approaching a comity problem it needs to be clear if it is applying the first or second kind. With judicial comity a court is saying \'96 it has jurisdiction but asks whether it should decline to exercise it because of comity to another n
ation. With prescriptive comity a court is asking whether its legislature has given it jurisdiction in the first place. That question it resolves by determining whether its legislature, having regard to the comity it is presumed to have extended to other s
overeign nations, has given to the statute an extraterritorial dimension. It will thus only conclude that it has jurisdiction if it is satisfied that was the lawmaker\'92s intention.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\ql\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 But the distinction amounts to more than a fine academic point. For as Scalia J points out, practice has shown that {\cf1 when exercising judicial}{\cf3  }comity, courts are generally reluctant to give up a jurisdiction which has been conferred upon them. With prescript
ive comity this reluctance may be less apparent since they have to decide whether jurisdiction has been conferred on them {\cf1 in the first place.}{\*\cs201{\*\updnprop10000}\up10\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\fs24\lang7177\loch\fs24\lang7177\cf1\ltrch\hich\i\loch\i  {\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s14\cf0\qj\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f6\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0{\ltrch\hich\f6\fs20\lang1033\loch\f6\fs20\lang1033 See page 652 of the judgment of Scalia J fn 9 }}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f6\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0{\ltrch\hich\f6\fs20\lang1033\i\loch\f6\fs20\lang1033\i \'93 Some antitrust courts, including the Court of Appeals in the present cases, have mistaken the comity at issue for the \'91comity of the courts,\'92 which has led them to characterize the question presented as one 
of abstention that is, whether they should \'91exercise or decline jurisdiction\'92\'85.As I shall discuss, that seems to be the error the Court has fallen into today. Because courts are very reluctant to refuse the exercise of conferred jurisdiction, confusion on 
this seemingly theoretical point can have the very practical consequence of greatly expending the territorial reach of the Sherman Act\'94.}}}}
}}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ai\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\i\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ai\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\i\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i\b0 Scalia J concludes that the issue in {\ul\ulc0 Hartford} is one of prescriptive comity. The Court had to decide how far Congress had intended the Sherman Act\'92s extraterritorial reach to extend. Based on the Restatement he argues that:}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\qj\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ai\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\i\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i {\rtlch \ltrch\loch \'93 }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i\b0 a nation having some basis for jurisdiction should nonetheless refrain from exercising jurisdiction when that exercise would be unreasonable.\'94}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\ql\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ai\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\i\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 Ansac argues that in interpreting section 3(1) we are faced with the task of determining prescriptive not judicial comity. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\ql\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0\ql\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 What Ansac seeks to take out of the dissent in {\ul\ulc0 Hartford} is that a statute must be interpreted in such a way that the legislature\'92s assertion of extraterritorial jurisdiction is reasonable. When Scalia J considers what reasonableness entails he refers to va
rious factors, which need not be repeated here, but amongst which he mentions \'93 the character of the activity to be regulated\'94, and the \'93extent to which the activity takes place within the territory of the regulating state\'94.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ai\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\i\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i\b0 But again this is stated in the context of comity or prescriptive comity as Scalia J preferred to characterise it. The Court in {\ul\ulc0 Hartford} was grappling with the issue of exercising jurisdiction over a reinsurance regulatory regime governing London markets.
 Scalia J makes his remarks in the context of one nation respecting the sovereign rights of another by limiting the reach of its laws. It is far removed from the facts of this matter where such a conflict does not arise.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
