\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\qj\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 It is also difficult to see why a party should be allowed to intervene and be afforded the procedural rights that section 53(1) affords and then not be entitled to argue for the imposition for relief at the end unless it has shown damages.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\qj\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ai\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\i\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i\b0 Furthermore no showing of damages is required in Tribunal procedures either as a matter of substantive or procedural law.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s14\cf0\qj\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f6\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0\ltrch\hich\f6\fs20\lang1033\loch\f6\fs20\lang1033 The award of damages is expressly reserved for civil courts .See sections 62(5) and 65(6).}}}
 The only exception is section 49 C(b)(i) which in interim relief procedures requires the Tribunal in deciding whether to grant inter
im relief to have regard to the \'93need to prevent serious or irreparable damage to the applicant\'94}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\qj\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ai\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\i\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ai\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\i\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i\b0 The reason for this is the fact that the Tribunal is not competent to award damages. It is thus unlikely that the legislature would have regarded the common law test for locus standi for breach of a statutory duty contingent on a showing of special damage
s to extend to relief in a body not competent to award damages. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ai\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\i\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i\b0 If Ansac is correct we would need to hear evidence that Botash had sustained damages to decide locus standi. This despite the fact that we have no jurisdiction to award damages or need to hear evidence that a complainant has suffered damages in order to m
ake a finding on the substantive issue of whether there is a prohibited practice. It would impose upon us an entirely superfluous enquiry premised on the application of a common law rule whose justification, paradoxically, is the elimination of adjudicatio
n of matters that are academic.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\ql\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ai\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 Ansac are however not prejudiced by the intervenors\'92 prayer for relief in the form of an interdict. If we should find that a prohibited practice has been established then Ansac is still entitled to be heard on the subject of relief. Relevant to such an enq
uiry is whether the relief sought by Botash is appropriate relief. To deny Botash the right to argue for such relief and for Ansac to dispute it would be to deny the Tribunal the opportunity to consider the appropriateness of a possible remedy. Allowing ou
r procedures to be used to air such a debate is a proper exercise of our discretion in arriving at what is \'91an appropriate order\'92. Foreclosing the possibility of such a debate as a gesture to a formal rule, lifted out of common law adversarial proceedings,
 is neither consonant with the objectives of the Act nor with our duties to perform a public function.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\ql\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ai\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\i\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ai\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\i\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057\i\b0 We find accordingly that Botash has locus standi to seek the relief it does in terms of the Act. Accordingly we do not need to consider whether it has established its locus standi in terms of the common law as in the alternative it does, nor do we need to
 consider whether Ansac has waived its rights to object.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s19\cf0\qj\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang2057\loch\f4\fs24\lang2057 
